          <td  valign="top"><!-- #BeginEditable "Body" --> 
            <BR><table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0"><tr><td><font class="h1font"><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 border=0 width=100%><TR><td><font class="h1font">Articles</td><form method='post' action=''><input type="hidden" name="PHPSESSID" value="528d771ccf1bf8d96505bad8695b02e4" /><td align='right' valign='bottom'><select name='select' onChange='go(this)'><option selected>More DeckTech Articles</option><option value='#'> </option><option value='/starwarsccg/articles/index.php3'>Star Wars: CCG</option><option value='/lotr/articles/articles.php'>Lord of the Rings</option><option value='/magination/articles/articles.php'>Magi-Nation Duel</option><option value='/swtcg/articles/articles.php'>Star Wars TCG</option></select></td></form></tr></table></font></td></tr><tr><td><table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0">
<tr height="10"><td width="98%" bgcolor="#333333" height="10"><img src="/magic/gfx/trans.gif" width="6" height="2" vspace="0" hspace="0" border="0"></td><td valign="bottom" align="right"><img src="/magic/gfx/hrz/tk.gif" width="103" height="10" border="0" vspace="0" hspace="0"></td>
</tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td><td valign="top" align="right">
<img src="/magic/gfx/hrz/bk.gif" width="92" height="24" border="0" vspace="0" hspace="0"></td>
</tr></table></td></tr><tr><td><font class="bfont"><font class="h1font"> Timmy, Johnny, and Spike<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/magic/gfx/star2.gif" width="20" height="20" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/magic/gfx/star2.gif" width="20" height="20" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/magic/gfx/star2.gif" width="20" height="20" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/magic/gfx/star2.gif" width="20" height="20" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(4.33)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/magic/main/mpage.php?member=4008'>Lyle "Pikachu87" Waldman</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/magic/main/mpage.php?member=4008&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> August 11, 2002</font><p align='justify'><font class="bfont"> Hi everyone.  Before I begin, let me explain where the idea from this article comes from.  Timmy, Johnny, and Spike was an article on Magicthegathering.com which I thought would be neat to bring to DT for all the Magic players who don&#39;t go to mtg.com.  Now, on with the article.<br />
<br />
Wizards of the Coast, in their playtesting and set development, has to think of many things.  They have to make certain cards which cater to Timmy, Johnny, and Spike.  No, no one works at Wizards (to my knowledge) named Timmy, Johnny, or Spike.  These three names were made up by Wizards R&D to define player types.  Because I like to serve myself first, let&#39;s first look at my type, Johnny.<br />
<br />
A Johnny is a player who basically looks at Magic as an intelectual game.  &quot;How can I make these cards work together?&quot;, &quot;Which cards work well with this?&quot;, and &quot;How can I build a tournament-winning deck out of a bunch of commons?&quot; are common phrases a Johnny might say to himself.  Johnnys don&#39;t like any particular card, bu they like the way cards interact.  A surefire way to define a Johnny are combo decks.  Johnnys love combo decks.  Any card that may work well with other cards are a Johnny&#39;s dream.  For instance, Sneak Attack is a Johnny card.  So is Dromar the Banisher (I think it&#39;s him...it&#39;s the dicard dragon).  Some other Johnny cards include Gaea&#39;s Blessing, Transcendence, and (sometimes) Millstone.  Jay Moldenhauer-Salazar (a writer on Mtg.com and one of the only ones whose articles I read) once wrote an article about the Cult of Transcendence, people who think Transcendence is a game-winning superpower card.  I am a proud member of this group.  Most Johnnys are also Cult (of Transcendence) members.<br />
<br />
Next, we&#39;ll look at Timmy.  Timmy is almost the exact opposite of Johnny.  Timmys generally like the biggest, baddest monstrosities there are.  Some Timmy cards include Phyrexian Dreadnought, Skyshroud Behemoth, Verdant Force, and Force of Nature.<br />
<br />
Both Timmy and Johnny have fun with Magic.  They enjoy it as a social activity.  If they win, they win with flare or by a big margin.  If they lose, but they won big previously, they&#39;ve had fun.  To quote Mark Rosewater, writer of the original Timmy, Johnny and Spike article, &quot;Timmy cares more about the quality of his win than the quantity of his wins. For example, Timmy sits down and plays ten games. He only wins three games out of ten but the three he wins, he dominates his opponent. Timmy had fun. Timmy walks away happy....Like Timmy, Johnny cares more about the quality of his wins than the quantity. For example, let&#39;s say Johnny builds a new deck that has a neat but difficult way to win. He plays ten games and manages to get his deck to do its thing once. Johnny walks away happy.&quot;<br />
<br />
Now let&#39;s look at Spike.  Spike is a lot like Timmy, and a little like Johnny.  Spike plays with whatever is good.  Unfortunately my article about Blue Countermagic was never submitted due to an error in the Decktech mainframe or whatever, but it mentioned a deck called Palinchron/High Tide.  For all who don&#39;t know this deck, you use Tolarian academy and a bunch of islands and artifacts to repeatedly play Palinchron and untap lands while playing High Tide.  Soon enough, you have enough mana to deck your opponent with a huge Stroke of Genius.  This is a Spike/Johnny type deck.  Johnny originally created it, but Spike loves to win.  No matter what, Spike must win every game.  Spike will copy Johnny&#39;s deck if Spike sees Johnny&#39;s deck wins.  Any moderately-costed card with a good ability in its own right is a Spike card.  Examples of Spike cards: Giant Growth, Spidersilk Armor, Call of the Herd, most counterspells, most burn spells.<br />
<br />
Spike is not a casual player at all.  To quote Maro again, &quot;For example, Spike plays ten games and wins nine of them. If Spike feels he should have won the tenth, he walks away unhappy.&quot;<br />
<br />
There are also mixed types.  I know for myself that I am a Johnny, but when I first took the survey, I came out as a Johnny/Timmy.  This basically means that I like good cards which get even better when in combination with other cards, i.e. Verdant Force, Sliver Queen, Skyshroud Behemoth, the new Dragon Legends, Congregation, etil next time, Chao!<br />
 <br></font><BR><font class="bfont"> <A HREF='/magic/articles/articles.php?id=3959&view=1&PHPSESSID=528d771ccf1bf8d96505bad8695b02e4'>Read the Reviews</a><font class="bfont"> | <A HREF='/magic/articles/articles.php?PHPSESSID=528d771ccf1bf8d96505bad8695b02e4'>Back to List</A></font><p><font class="bfont"> <b>You must be a member to contribute to Decktech.</b>  <p>Please <a href='/magic/main/join.php?PHPSESSID=528d771ccf1bf8d96505bad8695b02e4'> become a registered member</a></font><BR></td></tr></table>
